messages.content: 10.5: sorry.
PH: What
PH: Who is 10.5

Voreverl wakes up in a featureless expanse of void. Eric Zeety is there. He looks around.

"...Mhm. I figured."

Voreverl remains silent for a few moments, before letting out a scream "AAAAAAAAUUUUGGGHHH!!! Great, wonderful, just what I wanted, back to this death trap! I-I guess it makes sense, this is where I belong, isn't it!? I get to be Bernard Zie again, like I was meant to be! It's all I *can* be now anyway!"
"Hey, it's not too bad. You've got, uh, that weird robot, right? He's a good ally."
"Oh, yes, the one who's undyingly loyal to my body! What a perfect reminder of how I can never be Voreverl Leocot! Just some pathetic wannabe hero, and a man at that! Could I have failed *more*!?"

Eric laughs. "I'm sorry, but who cares? I mean this is--ngh." His form flickers. "This is the ultimate betrayal from all of reality. A key moment in your arc. Frankly, you should be disappointed it was so minor. You're no more a man than Caesar a republican."

"You don't get it... there is no arc! There is no rise to villainy! Not anymore, not ever! Sure, you can laugh it off because you're the one who still gets to be you! You don't know what it's like... no one does!"

“Please. Don’t go saying things like that.” 

Eric smirks. “Besides… well, just one time I’d like to be a little cheeky. I do know what it’s like. Did you like… think Eric Zeety was my *name*? Like, from the illustrious Zeety family? I can get and appreciate calling me what I express I want to be called, but you never once asked about it.” He laughs. “I guess I’m grateful. Identity’s a tricky thing.”
“I took it from a visual novel. It’s kind of embarrassing.”
((No way…))

"..." Voreverl stares blankly at him, before breaking into a smirk "Pffftt- gwhehahahah! Like, those dating games? That's... that's..." her expression darkens "Sorry, at least you know who you are. But still, that's totally different! A name change? Yeah, big deal! My- No, Voreverl Leocot's body doesn't belong to me! I have to restart from the ground up! I... I've wasted my entire life thinking I could be something I just wasn't!"

“Pft. Nobody’s in their own body. As far back as the Antarctica thing, I think all the participants were already being moved into identical vessels for convenience. And I don’t think the version of anyone that exists in the other realm can ever be called the same physical thing. It’s… it would also be the same for anyone people chose to bring with them.” Eric slumps over, and switches to a sitting position on the ground. “The body dysmorphia’s a real bitch, sure, but doesn’t this reveal mean you’ve already won? You were planning to take control of both your and Bernard Zie’s bodies, and you’ve done that already.”

"I... I don't feel in control. The body I use in Arctica, *my* body," Voreverl cringes "spent its whole life controlled by some creep I've never even met! And- and the one on Earth, I was just supposed to make use of it temporarily! It was a mistake that I ever grew up in it! But... but I liked that body... I felt like Voreverl Leocot when I was in it... it's only since I saw myself in my original body that I've started... Ugh! I'm not supposed to feel like this!"

“This really could’ve all been timed better.” Eric gives a weary laugh. His image distorts again. “So you take control. You make the way you’re ‘supposed’ to feel your bitch. Do whatever you want. Decimate Bernard Zie in revenge. Or don’t. This is all kind of tangential.”

Voreverl's eyes light up "Yes... Bernard Zie... it's his fault! He's the one who ruined my life! If he had just stayed in his lane in Arctica... Gweheheh! I just need to get rid of him, and there will be no competition for who gets to be Voreverl Leocot! That's how I take back control!"

He smiles awkwardly. “Whatever works.” Eric crosses his arms, gripping his sides. “Look, I just… you don’t get to have me with you in Arctica. It’s not your fault. There’s no way you could’ve known. But maybe this is fitting.” He coughs, clearing his throat.

“I always wondered how it would come across. When the day came. I think I always knew you’d end up learning at one point. That I’ve just been lying constantly.”

Voreverl looks concerned and reaches out a hand to try to help him up "Hey, what are you talking about? You're my top minion! Of course you're coming with me to Arctica! I only select winners for my army, so don't give me that quitters talk! Look... whatever it is you lied about doesn't matter! Stop messing around and take this seriously!"
((Mist Meric))

“I know. It’s really fucking selfish. You’ve always been way better at being the focus of the scene. I’ve been more than a little jealous at times, being in the background, but it’s fine. That’s my role. And it’s… all out of whack. You’re only supposed to be in this situation if you stomped someone brutally and evilly. None of that wimpy sympathy bait for a villain.”
Eric’s eyes go hazy and unfocused.
“But I’m not really in control of that. I guess I never had as much control as I thought I did.”

He strains himself to focus.
“This is the part where I die.”
((NOO))

"You- Wh- No! Shut up! Are you insane!? You... you can't be that much of a hypocrite! Tell me to take back control and then just... just up and die on me!? You're joking right!? What about the zoo!? What about all my schemes... I-I can handle them alone, of course, but... Look, just hang on, okay? We can... we can find help in Arctica, whatever's wrong! I'll pull some evil strings! That's what I do!"

“You can… hold onto that. Maybe you can pull something off. There’s a lot of miraculous stuff out there. And you’re pretty miraculous yourself. I’m not doing this to try to hold you back or anything. I just… I want to talk. If I’m not doing anything, I think it gets worse… this void unraveling me, absorbing me into its own.”

Eric’s foot slips, dangling slightly below where you’d infer the ‘floor’ is here.
“Yeah, it sure does. Whoops. You know the funniest fucking part? It’s that I know this can’t be the same both ways. I’m Eric Zeety. You’ve known me for some handful of months as a coworker who is mildly agreeable. But for me…”

“This past year or so, I— I’m happy. I was, I mean. Y’know. I went through each day excited just for what would happen in the day itself. The idea that I… that someone like me could live that way… it never would’ve come to my mind. Anyone’s.”

He smiles. “You gave that to me even when it was always going to be taken away one day. You’re a real crafty maniac.”

“Hey, enough of the sappy nonsense. Let’s get down to brass tacks. What this whole tale’s about. PH, TGP, TAP, GT, all the dumbass acronyms, the queen, Bernard Zie, John Leiblich, Mohammad Avdol, what fucking ever—it’s all a bunch of distractions. They’re the *other villains*. The minor foes you bump off or outlast to show what a big deal you are. The real focus, the protagonist of this story—that’s something else entirely.”

“I want to tell you everything I know. That’s how it’s supposed to work. Mysteries are for the detective, not the culprit. You should understand everything from the start. But I think if I tried to spoil everything, I’d be cut short immediately. A premonition. Maybe it’s worth the risk.”

“Well, that’s what I’ll ask of you. I’ll hold out. Maybe I can survive through this and serve as your minion again. In exchange… I want you to understand. Not the nonsense of every little world switch, the mechanics of magic, John Leiblich’s name lore. There’s way too much meaningless clutter in this project. I want you to know why you’re here. When you do… I think you’ll be able to win.”
“…Okay? It doesn’t matter if you betray me. As long as I can think you will.”

Voreverl takes a moment, and then nods "...It wouldn't be a proper betrayal unless I played along, now would it? Gweheheh, very well, minion! I, Voreverl Leocot, shall grant you this much! Not out of sympathy, but simply as a pragmatic, villainous decision! I've brought you here to torture the truth out of you, so give it to me, or suffer the consequences!"

He laughs. “Well, here’s one thing. Erica’s agreed to wire you like a billion dollars on Earth if you acknowledge her as the protagonist in the group chat. Just one opportunity you can try to take advantage of.”
((classic erica))

“Beyond that, uh…” He grimaces. “Ugh. TGP’s Dextrum, PH is Culbasko, SOUL is Oppineta… Wyrd and Zita Praxis are one and the same. Third guy involved with TAP is Sheeval Deltent, but he’s dead now. Oh, and Avdol—“
Eric screams in agony. “Fuck! Shit. Ghrk. There’s only so much that can happen.”

Eric’s more floating than resting on any clear surface by this point.
“Isidora, our boss - I think the TAP guys bought her out and that has something to do with what happened the first day. Take care of the flamingos till I’m back.”
“Pretty much everyone had at least one accomplice they knew that kept things running smoothly and set things up at their physical location.”

“It’s… it really hurts. It’s not even a physical pain it’s… my soul itself, my *sense* of self… everything’s being torn apart.” 
He squints.
“I’m not stopping until the last moment. You know about the Bernard Zie body switch, but that’s not the only time a child’s life was saved with this world switching stuff. The queen’s daughter Eulogia—she—it was sort of similar. Haruka Tanaka might know about that? I forget the logistics of everything. That’s the quasi-accomplice Rikarasu knew. She’s not actually related at all to George Tanaka, as far as I know. That’s a guy in Arctica. One of the original—oh, yeah, this part. There were originally twelve participants. Six from each place. You’re familiar with like, nine? Except Joliene doesn’t count, she was a last minute replacement for Eric Dextrum.”

“Maybe this is just a distraction. I don’t know what else to say. There’s so much I could say, so much I can’t. Even if I was free to do anything, could I find the words? I don’t think I… I wouldn’t know how.”

He shivers. “The participants who die, as well as certain people involved with the project, they end up having something to do with this idea of *observers*—“ The void begins encroaching on Eric Zeety, burying his body. “Well, I think I made a pretty economic use of time. …Goodbye, Voreverl Leocot. It was all a lot of fun.”

Voreverl was straining herself in thought trying to follow the exposition, but snaps back when she hears that and tries to force a grin "Th-that's it, huh... I... I guess this is what victory f-feels like...! Gwehah! Goodbye Eric Zeety! I cast you away as a stepping stone so that I can face superior foes with my own power!" She casts her eyes down, avoiding his gaze "And thank you... you're the best minion I could ask for."

Eric doesn’t have anything else to say.

And then he’s gone. Hopefully Voreverl can get over this. He was really just a joke character.
Voreverl hears footsteps behind her.
A man who looks like this emerges. “Excuse me, but, what exactly is all this?”
